Complex molecules in methylene orange (MO) dye-contaminated water are carcinogenic and mutagenic risks to human health. Carbon quantum dot surface-decorated titanium dioxide nanocomposites (CQD-TiO2 NCs) were synthesized via a sustainable hydrothermal method at concentrations of 1.5–3 mL. These NCs exhibits superior electron transfer, light harvesting capabilities, high stability, easy modification, optical characteristics, and photocatalytic properties. The surface morphology, porosity, physiochemical, and optical features of these CQD-TiO2 NCs were characterized using TEM, UV–Vis, PL, BET, BJH micromeritics, pHzpc, and photoelectrochemical measurements. The prepared NCs were evaluated against the photocatalytic degradation of MO dye molecules using a solar simulator system. The TEM revealed ultra-sensitive and tiny CQD materials with graphite phases ranging from 5 to 10 nm and attached to the octahedron surface of TiO2 NCs. The PL analysis observed three distinct emission peaks in the visible region, attributed to the near band edge, interstitial (Ti

                        i
                     ), and oxygen vacancy (V

                        0
                     ). The BET and BJH analyses were conducted to determine the N2 adsorption-desorption surface area and mesoporous structure with pore sizes ranging from 2 to 50 nm. These NCs showed excellent photocatalytic performance, effectively degrading MO up to 99.00 % in a 3 mL variation, indicating that they could be a great candidate for photocatalytic purification of wastewater containing MO dyes.

ce:section.ce:para:
The PL spectra were obtained to determine the luminescent properties of the prepared TiO2 and CQD-TiO2 NCs under an excitation wavelength of 420 nm (Fig. 4
                        ). The PL spectrum of TiO2 showed an emission peak in the visible light region at a wavelength of 450 nm, attributed to band-edge excitation and shallow trap states. Upon the integration of CQDs with TiO2, the interactions between those materials lead changes to the band gap. It can be seen that three peaks are observed, where the highest peak is attributed to near band edge (NBE) emission, the second highest peak is associated with interstitial titanium (Ti

                           i

                        ), and the low peak represents oxygen vacancy (V

                           0
                        ) (Fig. 5
                        (a–e)). CQDs can act as electron donors or acceptors, which can cause changes in the electron distribution in TiO2. This caused a change in energy levels at the conduction and valence bands, which ultimately affects the band gap value of the NC material. In addition, the spatial distribution of colloidal quantum dots also influenced the optical characteristics of the NCs.

N₂ adsorption-desorption from BET and BJH methods was performed to assess the surface area and porosity (pore size distribution and volume) of the materials using N₂ liquid at 77 K. Fig. 6
                        (a–e) presented the N₂ adsorption-desorption isotherms and the corresponding pore size distributions (insets) for TiO and CQD-TiO₂ NCs with varying CQD concentrations. The isotherms were identified as type IV in accordance with IUPAC standards through hysteresis loops, which indicate mesoporous structures. The insets in Fig. 6 revealed a uniform pore size distribution with multiple distinct peaks, indicating a pore size range between 2 nm and 50 nm (Table 2
                        ). The integration of CQDs into TiO₂ samples led to a significant enhancement in specific surface area compared to pure TiO₂. Among the samples, V3 exhibited the highest specific surface area and smallest pore size. However, it was less effective in degrading MO with the addition of 2.5 mL CQDs. In contrast, the V4 sample with a larger pore size and a decreased surface area demonstrated better MO degradation performance. The BJH analysis indicated that the addition of CQDs significantly influenced the surface area, pore volume, and pore size of TiO₂. Furthermore, the integration of CQDs enhances the surface area of TiO₂ due to the occurrence of several factors including heating temperature, reaction time, and solvent type; each of these factors can strongly affect the properties of the composite materials [52]. Increased temperature and long reaction times often lead to larger pore sizes. In addition, CQDs tend to agglomerate at higher concentrations due to interactions like van der Waals forces and hydrogen bonds [53]. CQD nucleation plays a role in the formation of larger TiO2 crystals. At higher concentrations, CQDs will interfere with the nucleation control of larger crystal growth. The positioning effect is advantageous in the photocatalysis process because it enhances delivery efficiency, increases surface area, and improves energy transfer [54,55]. TEM and BET analyses revealed that the size of NCs is favorable for achieving high photocatalytic effectiveness. Table 2 summarizes the findings of BET testing.
